  "prompt": "What would undivided India have looked like today? What portion of what is now Pakistan and Bangladesh would have been non-Muslim?",
  "response": "It is a complex and speculative exercise to determine what undivided India (i.e., pre-partition British India) would look like today and the demographic distribution within it. The partition of British India in 1947 created two separate nations, India and Pakistan, which later led to the creation of Bangladesh in 1971. To understand the religious demographic that might have persisted in an undivided India, we would need to look into historical data and trends.\n\n1. Historical Context:\nPrior to partition, British India had significant populations of Hindus, Muslims, Sikhs, Christians, and other religious groups spread across the regions that became India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh.\n\n2. Population Distribution Before Partition:\n- In areas that became Pakistan, specifically West Pakistan (now Pakistan), the population was predominantly Muslim but had sizable Hindu and Sikh minorities.\n- East Pakistan (now Bangladesh) had a majority Muslim population but also significant Hindu minority populations.\n- India itself had a mixed population of Hindus, Muslims, Sikhs, Christians, and others.\n\n3. Demographic Trends:\nIf we consider undivided India's population trends, large Muslim populations were concentrated in regions that became Pakistan and Bangladesh. However, in an undivided scenario, the demographic shifts over decades could have been influenced by several factors, including migration patterns, birth rates, urbanization, socioeconomic development, and political considerations.\n\nToday, Pakistan and Bangladesh are predominantly Muslim, with smaller non-Muslim populations (Hindus, Christians, etc.).\n\n- Pakistan: It has over 95% Muslims, with the remaining population consisting of Hindus, Christians, Sikhs, and others.\n- Bangladesh: Approximately 90% of the population is Muslim, with Hindus composing about 8-10%, and other religious groups making up the remaining percentage.\n\nIn an undivided India scenario:\n- Non-Muslim populations in what is now Pakistan and Bangladesh would likely be larger than they are today since the sizable migration of non-Muslims from these regions occurred during and after partition.\n- The demographic composition would possibly maintain higher percentages of Hindus and other non-Muslims in regions like Punjab, Sindh, and Bengal.\n\nHowever, these estimations are highly speculative, as many factors, including political policies, economic developments, social changes, and migrations, would have influenced the population dynamics over decades in an undivided India.",
